# Fylox Protocol Specification

Version: Draft  
Status: Early Specification  
Last Updated: 2026

---

# Overview

Fylox is an experimental payment infrastructure layer designed to explore real-world transaction flows within the Pi ecosystem.

The protocol focuses on enabling simple payment interactions between users and merchants using QR-based payment requests.

Fylox does not replace the underlying blockchain. Instead, it provides a lightweight layer that simplifies how users initiate and confirm transactions.

---

# Design Goals

The Fylox protocol is designed with the following goals:

• Simplicity — payment flows should be easy to understand and use  
• Real-world usability — focus on everyday transaction scenarios  
• Minimal infrastructure — avoid unnecessary complexity in early stages  
• Open design — allow future integrations and developer experimentation  

---

# Core Concept

Fylox introduces a simple interaction model between three main participants:

User  
Merchant  
Payment Layer (Fylox)

The protocol provides a structured way for a user to initiate a payment using a QR code generated by a merchant.

---

# Payment Flow

The basic payment process follows these steps:

1. Merchant generates a QR payment request.
2. User scans the QR code.
3. The payment request is interpreted by the Fylox interface.
4. The user sends a Pi transaction.
5. The merchant receives confirmation of the payment.

Simplified flow:

User  
↓  
Scan QR  
↓  
Fylox Payment Interface  
↓  
Pi Network Transaction  
↓  
Merchant Confirmation

---

# Payment Request Structure (Conceptual)

A payment request may contain:

• Merchant identifier  
• Payment amount (optional)  
• Payment description  
• Timestamp  
• Transaction reference  

This information allows the user interface to display a clear payment request before the transaction is executed.

---

# Merchant Interaction

Merchants interact with the protocol by generating payment requests.

In the MVP stage this can be as simple as:

• displaying a QR code  
• receiving payment confirmation  
• validating transaction completion  

Future versions may include additional merchant tools.

---

# User Interaction

Users interact with Fylox through a payment interface that allows them to:

• scan payment QR codes  
• review payment details  
• confirm Pi transactions  
• verify payment success  

The goal is to keep the process simple and understandable for everyday users.

---

# Protocol Scope (MVP)

The first version of Fylox focuses only on:

• QR payment requests  
• basic payment confirmation  
• simple merchant interactions  

Advanced infrastructure features are intentionally excluded from the MVP to keep the system simple and testable.

---

# Long-Term Architecture (Conceptual)

While the current Fylox implementation focuses on a simple QR-based payment layer, the long-term vision of the protocol may evolve into a multi-layer infrastructure designed to support broader economic activity.

These layers are conceptual and represent possible future directions for the project.

Potential layers may include:

1. Payment Layer  
Infrastructure for real-world transactions between users and merchants.

2. Merchant Infrastructure Layer  
Tools and interfaces that allow businesses to accept and manage Pi payments.

3. Application Integration Layer  
Interfaces that allow external applications and services to integrate payment capabilities.

4. Economic Activity Layer  
Systems that connect digital services, marketplaces, and other economic interactions with the payment infrastructure.

5. Governance and Coordination Layer  
Mechanisms that allow communities, developers, and stakeholders to participate in the evolution of the ecosystem.

These layers are exploratory and are not part of the current MVP implementation.

---

# Future Extensions

Possible future extensions may include:

• developer APIs  
• merchant dashboards  
• payment analytics  
• integration tools for applications  

These extensions are exploratory and may evolve as the project develops.

---

# Experimental Status

Fylox is an experimental open-source project.

The protocol specification may evolve significantly as new ideas are tested and validated.

The goal of this document is to describe the initial conceptual model of the protocol.
